# no_std Policy for the Shader Pipeline

## Feature flag meaning

- `std` = host-only conveniences (libstd, cranelift-native, anyhow, etc.)
- `std` does NOT mean "has a compiler"
- `glsl` = GLSL front-end (lps-naga). Independent of `std`.
- Default server builds include the full compiler. Opt-out features (e.g.
  `no-shader-compile`) exist only for stripped/test builds.

## What MUST work without `std`

- `lps-naga` — GLSL parsing via naga (`#![no_std]` + alloc)
- `lpir-cranelift` — LPIR → Cranelift → RISC-V machine code
- `lpir-cranelift::jit(source, options)` — full GLSL string entry point
- `lp-engine` `ShaderRuntime::compile_shader` — real compilation, not a stub
- `lp-server` — project/client management on bare metal

## Anti-patterns (do NOT do these)

- `#[cfg(feature = "std")] fn compile_shader(...)` with a stub `#[cfg(not(...))]`
- `#[cfg(feature = "std")] pub use compile::jit;` (jit must be available without std)
- Making `lps-naga` a `std`-only dependency of `lpir-cranelift`
- Suggesting "precompile shaders on host" as an alternative to on-device JIT
